{{Infobox book | name = The Giant Devil Dingo | title_orig = | translator = | image = | caption = | author = [[Dick Roughsey]] | illustrator = Dick Roughsey | cover_artist = Dick Roughsey | country = Australia | language = English | series = | subject = Aboriginal Australians - Folklore. Legends - Queensland - Cape York Peninsula. Dingo - Folklore. | genre = children, legends | publisher = Collins, Sydney | release_date = 1973 | media_type = | pages = 34 (Hardback) | isbn = 0-17-006470-0 | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''The Giant Devil Dingo''''' (1973) is a picture book for children by Dick Roughsey. It describes how the [[dreamtime]] devil-dingo, Gaiya, of lower [[Cape York Peninsula]] mythology was domesticated to become man's friend and helper.
Artwork from the book is held by the [[National Museum of Australia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://collectionsearch.nma.gov.au/object/46425 |title=Painting no. 12, Giant Devil-Dingo Series by Dick Roughsey - The people cutting up Gaiya. |website=www.nma.gov.au |publisher=National Museum of Australia |accessdate=16 June 2016}}</ref>
==Reception== [[Kirkus Reviews]] wrote "The appendix might better have been a preface ... But the chase and basic situation (in Europe the hungry pursuers would be a witch and her familiar) are as easy to grasp as the peculiarly Australian flavor is authentic. And despite the sameness of the scenes--repetitive in scale, perspective and color--Roughsey's flat, clay colored paintings (with dabs of green for foliage) are the more effective for their amateur look--especially where that huge-tongued, red-eyed dingo opposes the small, faceless, dimly differentiated humans."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/dick-roughsey/the-giant-devil-dingo/ |title=The Giant Devil-Dingo|website=www.kirkusreviews.com |publisher=Kirkus Media LLC |accessdate=16 June 2016}}</ref> while ''The Aboriginal Child at School'' called it "a highly successful book."<ref>{{cite journal |date=April 1974 |title=Book Reviews |url=http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayAbstract?fromPage=online&aid=9396459&fileId=S1326011100003586 |journal=The Aboriginal Child at School |publisher=Cambridge University Press |volume=2 |issue=2 |pages=58–59 |accessdate=16 June 2016}}</ref>''The Giant Devil Dingo'' has also been reviewed by ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'' and ''Reading Time''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.austlit.edu.au/austlit/page/C317845 |title=The Giant Devil Dingo |website=www.austlit.edu.au |publisher=AustLit |accessdate=16 June 2016}}</ref> It has been selected for the 2010 NSW [[Premier's Reading Challenge]],<ref>{{cite web | url=https://products.schools.nsw.edu.au/prc/booklist/listBooksByTitle.html?letter=G&levelId=3 |title=NSW Premier's Reading Challenge 2010 |accessdate= 30 November 2009 }}</ref> and was commended in the 1974 [[Children's Book Council of Australia]] awards for Children's Picture Book of the Year.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://cbca.org.au/7079.htm |title = The Children's Book Council of Australia, Winners and Commended Books, 1974. |accessdate = 30 November 2009 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141216052001/http://cbca.org.au/7079.htm |archivedate = 16 December 2014 |df = }}</ref>
